<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/Sport/Article&sz=300x250&c=1947207329&t=artid%3d785c1bbd-a588-4db0-adeb-564ba1319806%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/Sport/Article&sz=300x250&c=1947207329&t=artid%3d785c1bbd-a588-4db0-adeb-564ba1319806%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>As a further boost Banyana’s star midfielder, Thembi Kgatlana, was nominated for Caf Women’s Player of the Year alongside Asisat Oshoala of Nigeria and Gabrielle Onguene of Cameroon.The awards ceremony will be held in Accra, Ghana, on 4 January.Smeda, who also played a key role when Banyana clinched the Cosafa Cup, scoring four goals in the tournament, said it was amazing to be counted as one of the best three  teams in Africa. “Being recognised, making the final top three is an achievement on its own. It shows that this year we had one of our best years yet. The recognition proves we’re getting something right,” said the veteran midfielder.Smeda was full of praise for her 21-year-old teammate Kgatlana, who took home the Player of the Tournament accolade at the Cosafa event.“I’m proud of Thembi – she has grown as a player and I believe she will go far.”Smeda added that winning the Caf accolade would be a mental boost for them as they face a hectic schedule next year. Banyana will start the year with two back-to-back friendlies against Sweden in Cape Town as part of their preparations for Africa Women’s Cup of Nations (Women’s Afcon) qualifiers.Said Smeda: “Winning the accolade could set the tone for us. We want to qualify for the Women’s Afcon and ensure that we finish in the top three. Many players in our team, myself included, have never played in a World Cup. That is something many of us want to achieve before our football careers are over.”
